{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488401"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:40:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:40:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"431"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/431"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.61,0.15,0.08,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"431"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81617"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/431"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"431"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66943"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"128"},{"type":"tags","id":"909"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7684"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42084"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81617"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of worsening shortness of breath and sharp chest pain that is worse when lying flat and with deep breathing. She has been unwell with flu-like symptoms for the past week. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly distressed. Her pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Her jugular venous pressure is elevated at 4 cm. Chest examination reveals bibasal crepitations. Heart sounds are normal with no rub audible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn electrocardiogram shows diffuse ST elevation and PR depression with reciprocal ST depression in aVR. A chest X-ray shows an increased cardiothoracic ratio of 0.6 with a globular cardiac appearance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aspirin and clopidogrel","Ibuprofen and colchicine","Furosemide","Pericardiocentesis","Prednisolone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features typical of acute pericarditis, likely viral in origin given the preceding flu-like illness. The diagnosis is supported by several classic features: pleuritic chest pain worse when supine, recent viral prodrome, and characteristic ECG changes of diffuse ST elevation with PR depression. The chest X-ray showing cardiac enlargement suggests an associated pericardial effusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIbuprofen and colchicine\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial treatment. NSAIDs are the cornerstone of treatment for acute pericarditis, providing both symptomatic relief and treating the underlying inflammation. The addition of colchicine has been shown in randomised trials to reduce symptom duration and recurrence rates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin and clopidogrel\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for acute coronary syndrome, but the diffuse nature of the ECG changes and the clinical context make this diagnosis less likely. In acute coronary syndrome, ST elevation is typically regional rather than diffuse and PR depression is not seen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E might temporarily improve symptoms of fluid overload but does not address the underlying inflammatory process. It should be reserved for cases where there is significant fluid overload not responding to anti-inflammatory treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericardiocentesis\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated for cardiac tamponade, which this patient does not have. While there is evidence of some haemodynamic compromise with elevated JVP, there are no features of tamponade such as hypotension, pulsus paradoxus, or electrical alternans.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E should be avoided as initial therapy in viral or idiopathic pericarditis as it may increase the risk of recurrence. Corticosteroids are reserved for specific causes of pericarditis (e.g., autoimmune) or cases refractory to NSAIDs and colchicine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute pericarditis typically presents with pleuritic chest pain, diffuse ST elevation with PR depression on ECG, and may follow a viral illness.","First-line treatment for acute pericarditis is combination therapy with NSAIDs and colchicine.","ECG changes in acute pericarditis include diffuse ST elevation with PR depression and reciprocal changes in aVR."],"references":["Troughton, R., Asher, C. and Klein, A., 2004. Pericarditis. The Lancet, 363(9410), pp.717-727.","Adler, Y., Charron, P., Imazio, M., Badano, L., Bar\u00f3n-Esquivias, G., Bogaert, J., Brucato, A., Gueret, P., Klingel, K., Lionis, C., Maisch, B., Mayosi, B., Pavie, A., Risti\u0107, A., Sabat\u00e9 Tenas, M., Seferovic, P., Swedberg, K. and Tomkowski, W., 2015. 2015 ESC Guidelines for the diagnosis and management of pericardial diseases. European Heart Journal, 36(42), pp.2921-2964.","Hoit, B. 2022. Constrictive Pericarditis. UptoDate. Viewed on November 2022. https://www.uptodate.com/contents/constrictive-pericarditis?search=constrictive%20pericarditis\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~110\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1#H2715225172","Sharma I, Nugent JG, Sullivan PD, Mansoor AM. Jugular venous pulse in constrictive pericarditis. BMJ Case Reports CP. 2020 Apr 1;13(4):e233078.","Welch TD. Constrictive pericarditis: diagnosis, management and clinical outcomes. Heart. 2018 May 1;104(9):725-31."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66943"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"431"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66943"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T15:23:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T15:24:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"431"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81617"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":